Here’s a summary of the latest code changes, most recent first.

Reuters (LSEG) as primary source — GDM Cash Bonds

	•	Added a source_mode selector to the Cash Bonds calibrator config, defaulting to “Reuters (LSEG) only” (the only feasible feed now), with an “All available sources” option for later.
	•	Reworked _sources() to honour that mode and pass params through all three callers (calibrate, backtest, candidate_flags), so Reuters-only output is a clean single-column subset of the full four-source design.

Business benefit / false-positive identification

	•	Reframed ground truth to your real semantics in column_map.py: GENUINE_STATUSES (L2-confirmed = true positive) and L1_FP_STATUSES (L1-closed = false positive).
	•	Added EPE resolution fields (resolution_level, outcome) to the mock, and coupled the mock so genuine exceptions point at genuinely off-market trades — and fixed the trade IDs to a per-date scheme so BRV↔EPE actually join.
	•	Added a candidate_flags() method to all three calibrators (GFX, Cash Bonds, default) plus candidate_flags_checks() in the service.
	•	Added _labels() and _business_benefit() in the threshold router, and a minutes_per_l1 input; the backtest now returns FP-eliminated, TP-retained, ops-hours-saved, and join match-rate.
	•	Added a Business Benefit panel to the Backtesting tab UI, including the join-health warning that explains the near-zero precision you’d seen.

GDM Cash Bonds calibrator (the bigger rebuild)

	•	New composite-key, per-source calibrator: key = sub-type + rating region + tenor + credit rating + issuer rating + notional range, with a granularity selector and a sparsity fallback to product level.
	•	Per-source thresholds (BVAL/RDAM/Reuters/EOD) by percentile or MAD, OR alerting across sources, wired into both calibration and backtesting.
	•	Split the old generic per-check engine into default_calibrator.py (now the is_default fallback) so unregistered products still work; registry now selects the default via the is_default flag.
	•	Extended the mock with Cash Bonds dimensions and per-source reference prices.
